<subSubSection id="0AADF9843663226FFF09FC4F848FFF76" lastPageId="30" lastPageNumber="1572" pageId="29" pageNumber="1571" type="description">
<paragraph id="4208AA0F3663226CFF09FC4F8683FC5B" blockId="29.[212,1171,917,974]" pageId="29" pageNumber="1571">
Forewing length: male 
<quantity id="854F07EA3663226CFE0AFC4F860AFC3B" box="[471,609,917,941]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.575" metricValueMax="3.05" metricValueMin="2.1" pageId="29" pageNumber="1571" unit="mm" value="25.75" valueMax="30.5" valueMin="21.0">21–30.5 mm</quantity>
(mean (
<emphasis id="70C3761D3663226CFD60FC4C86A1FC38" box="[701,714,918,942]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="1571">n</emphasis>
= 6) 
<quantity id="854F07EA3663226CFCDAFC4F8712FC3B" box="[775,889,917,941]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.658" pageId="29" pageNumber="1571" unit="mm" value="26.58">26.58 mm</quantity>
, 
<collectingRegion id="807364ED3663226CFC59FC4F87C3FC3B" box="[900,936,917,941]" country="Serbia" name="Sid" pageId="29" pageNumber="1571">SD</collectingRegion>
= 3.150); female 
<quantity id="854F07EA3663226CFBB1FC4F8548FC5B" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.45" metricValueMax="2.8" metricValueMin="2.1" pageId="29" pageNumber="1571" unit="mm" value="24.5" valueMax="28.0" valueMin="21.0">21– 28 mm</quantity>
(mean (
<emphasis id="70C3761D3663226CFE5EFC6C85FBFC58" box="[387,400,950,974]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="1571">n</emphasis>
= 7) 
<quantity id="854F07EA3663226CFE0FFC6F862DFC5B" box="[466,582,949,973]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.411" pageId="29" pageNumber="1571" unit="mm" value="24.11">24.11 mm</quantity>
, 
<collectingRegion id="807364ED3663226CFD8EFC6F861CFC5B" box="[595,631,949,973]" country="Serbia" name="Sid" pageId="29" pageNumber="1571">SD</collectingRegion>
= 1.953).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4208AA0F3663226CFF09FBDC80EFFACA" blockId="29.[212,1172,1029,1691]" pageId="29" pageNumber="1571">
<emphasis id="70C3761D3663226CFF09FBDC855EFB88" box="[212,309,1030,1054]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="1571">Records.</emphasis>
Bukoba, 
<collectingRegion id="807364ED3663226CFE75FBDF8591FB8B" box="[424,506,1029,1053]" country="Tanzania" name="Rukwa" pageId="29" pageNumber="1571">Rukwa</collectingRegion>
basin and Northern Highlands; found in open woodland and open montane forest, to 
<quantity id="854F07EA3663226CFDC0FBFF861BFBAB" box="[541,624,1061,1085]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="29" pageNumber="1571" unit="m" value="2000.0">2000 m</quantity>
(
<bibRefCitation id="2626D7FE3663226CFDA2FBFF8774FBAB" author="Kielland J" box="[639,799,1061,1085]" pageId="29" pageNumber="1571" refId="ref25501" refString="Kielland J. 1990. Butterflies of Tanzania. Melbourne: Hill House." type="book" year="1990">Kielland 1990</bibRefCitation>
, p.64). 
<bibRefCitation id="2626D7FE3663226CFCABFBFF8041FBAB" author="Cordeiro NJ" box="[886,1066,1061,1085]" pageId="29" pageNumber="1571" pagination="25 - 41" refId="ref25137" refString="Cordeiro NJ. 1990. A provisional, annotated checklist of the butterflies in Lake Manyara National Park, Arusha region, Tanzania. J East Afr Nat Hist Soc Natl Mus. 80: 25 - 41." type="journal article" year="1990">Cordeiro (1990)</bibRefCitation>
recorded this taxon from Lake 
<collectingRegion id="807364ED3663226CFE39FB9F8627FBCB" box="[484,588,1093,1117]" country="Tanzania" name="Manyara" pageId="29" pageNumber="1571">Manyara</collectingRegion>
National Park. Although Kielland did not give specific records for 
<collectingRegion id="807364ED3663226CFE69FBBF862AFBEB" box="[436,577,1125,1149]" country="Tanzania" name="Kilimanjaro" pageId="29" pageNumber="1571">Kilimanjaro</collectingRegion>
, and the butterfly was not encountered in the forest zone by 
<bibRefCitation id="2626D7FE3663226CFEEFFB5F85AEFB0B" author="Liseki SD" box="[306,453,1157,1181]" pageId="29" pageNumber="1571" refId="ref25599" refString="Liseki SD. 2009. Butterfly diversity and its relevance to conservation in north-eastern Tanzania [PhD thesis). Canterbury (UK): University of Kent." type="book" year="2009">Liseki (2009)</bibRefCitation>
, it is included here as a member of the lower slopes fauna based on a female in BMNH from W. 
<collectingRegion id="807364ED3663226CFD92FB7F86B7FB2B" box="[591,732,1189,1213]" country="Tanzania" name="Kilimanjaro" pageId="29" pageNumber="1571">Kilimanjaro</collectingRegion>
, 
<quantity id="854F07EA3663226CFD37FB7F8714FB2B" box="[746,895,1189,1213]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4478" metricValueMax="1.524" metricValueMin="1.3716" pageId="29" pageNumber="1571" unit="ft" value="4750.0" valueMax="5000.0" valueMin="4500.0">4500–5000 ft</quantity>
, collected in 1937 by B. Cooper, and a pair from 
<collectingRegion id="807364ED3663226CFDC0FB1F86CCFB4B" box="[541,679,1221,1245]" country="Tanzania" name="Kilimanjaro" pageId="29" pageNumber="1571">Kilimanjaro</collectingRegion>
collected by F.J. Jackson. In addition, OUMNH has a male from Taveta, and a female from 
<collectingRegion id="807364ED3663226CFC48FB3E8049FB6A" box="[917,1058,1252,1276]" country="Tanzania" name="Kilimanjaro" pageId="29" pageNumber="1571">Kilimanjaro</collectingRegion>
, both ex Rogers. Beyond 
<collectingCountry id="3AA0EA9F3663226CFE41FADE866EFA8A" box="[412,517,1284,1308]" name="Tanzania" pageId="29" pageNumber="1571">Tanzania</collectingCountry>
this subspecies occurs in 
<collectingCountry id="3AA0EA9F3663226CFC9FFADE87E7FA8A" box="[834,908,1284,1308]" name="Sudan" pageId="29" pageNumber="1571">Sudan</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="3AA0EA9F3663226CFC43FADE8069FA8A" box="[926,1026,1284,1308]" name="Ethiopia" pageId="29" pageNumber="1571">Ethiopia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="3AA0EA9F3663226CFBC9FADE803AFA8A" box="[1044,1105,1284,1308]" name="Democratic Republic of the Congo" pageId="29" pageNumber="1571">DRC</collectingCountry>
(east Kivu), 
<collectingCountry id="3AA0EA9F3663226CFEFBFAFE85EAFAAA" box="[294,385,1316,1340]" name="Uganda" pageId="29" pageNumber="1571">Uganda</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="3AA0EA9F3663226CFE63FAFE8667FAAA" box="[446,524,1316,1340]" name="Kenya" pageId="29" pageNumber="1571">Kenya</collectingCountry>
. More widely, the species occurs across much of central Africa, from 
<collectingCountry id="3AA0EA9F3663226CFEB6FA9E85AAFACA" box="[363,449,1348,1372]" name="Senegal" pageId="29" pageNumber="1571">Senegal</collectingCountry>
to 
<collectingCountry id="3AA0EA9F3663226CFE34FA9E8621FACA" box="[489,586,1348,1372]" name="Ethiopia" pageId="29" pageNumber="1571">Ethiopia</collectingCountry>
and south to 
<collectingCountry id="3AA0EA9F3663226CFD31FA9E872FFACA" box="[748,836,1348,1372]" name="Zambia" pageId="29" pageNumber="1571">Zambia</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="2626D7FE3663226CFC89FA9E804DFACA" author="Ackery PR &amp; Smith CR &amp; Vane-Wright RI" box="[852,1062,1348,1372]" pageId="29" pageNumber="1571" refId="ref24360" refString="Ackery PR, Smith CR, Vane-Wright RI, editors. 1995. Carcasson' s African butterflies: an annotated catalogue of the Papilionoidea and Hesperioidea of the Afrotropical Region. East Melbourne (Australia): CSIRO." type="book" year="1995">Ackery et al. 1995</bibRefCitation>
, p.212).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4208AA0F3663226FFF23FABE848FFF76" blockId="29.[212,1172,1029,1691]" lastBlockId="30.[144,1103,168,224]" lastPageId="30" lastPageNumber="1572" pageId="29" pageNumber="1571">
Males are white, with or without a black forewing apex and margin; females are mostly fairly similar, more or less lightly maculated, and generally with a greyishyellow cast. 
<bibRefCitation id="2626D7FE3663226CFE80FA7E8584FA2A" author="Larsen TB" box="[349,495,1444,1468]" pageId="29" pageNumber="1571" refId="ref25550" refString="Larsen TB. 1996. The butterflies of Kenya and their natural history. 2 nd edn. Oxford (UK): Oxford University Press." type="book" year="1996">Larsen (1996</bibRefCitation>
, p.143) states that “The smaller 
<taxonomicName id="85B7D18C3663226CFC81FA7E87A0FA2A" authorityName="Ackery et al." authorityYear="1995" baseAuthorityName="Boisduval" baseAuthorityYear="1833" box="[860,971,1444,1468]" class="Insecta" family="Pieridae" genus="Dixeia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="1571" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="orbona">
<emphasis id="70C3761D3663226CFC81FA7E87A0FA2A" box="[860,971,1444,1468]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="1571">D. orbona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is very similar [to 
<taxonomicName id="85B7D18C3663226CFF09FA1E8552FA4A" baseAuthorityName="Boisduval" baseAuthorityYear="1836" box="[212,313,1476,1500]" class="Insecta" family="Pieridae" genus="Dixeia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="1571" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pigea">
<emphasis id="70C3761D3663226CFF09FA1E8552FA4A" box="[212,313,1476,1500]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="1571">D. pigea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
] and the two may be impossible to tell apart”. 
<bibRefCitation id="2626D7FE3663226CFC4CFA1E8053FA4A" author="Talbot G" box="[913,1080,1476,1500]" pageId="29" pageNumber="1571" pagination="102 - 112" refId="ref26272" refString="Talbot G. 1943 b. Notes on the genus Dixeia Talbot, with descriptions of new forms (Lep. Rhop. Pieridae). Proc R Entomol Soc Lond. 12: 102 - 112." type="journal article" year="1943">Talbot (1943b</bibRefCitation>
, p.106) originally indicated that female 
<taxonomicName id="85B7D18C3663226CFD8DFA3E86E0FA6A" baseAuthorityName="Boisduval" baseAuthorityYear="1836" box="[592,651,1508,1532]" class="Insecta" family="Pieridae" genus="Dixeia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="1571" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pigea">
<emphasis id="70C3761D3663226CFD8DFA3E86E0FA6A" box="[592,651,1508,1532]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="1571">pigea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(“fw. 
<quantity id="854F07EA3663226CFD00FA3E8733FA6A" box="[733,856,1508,1532]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.9" metricValueMax="3.2" metricValueMin="2.6" pageId="29" pageNumber="1571" unit="mm" value="29.0" valueMax="32.0" valueMin="26.0">26–32 mm</quantity>
”) were larger than female 
<taxonomicName id="85B7D18C3663226CFF09F9DE854BF98A" authorityName="Ackery et al." authorityYear="1995" baseAuthorityName="Boisduval" baseAuthorityYear="1833" box="[212,288,1540,1564]" class="Insecta" family="Pieridae" genus="Dixeia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="1571" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="orbona">
<emphasis id="70C3761D3663226CFF09F9DE854BF98A" box="[212,288,1540,1564]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="1571">orbona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(“fore-wing 
<quantity id="854F07EA3663226CFE64F9D98658F98D" box="[441,563,1539,1564]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.3" metricValueMax="2.5" metricValueMin="2.1" pageId="29" pageNumber="1571" unit="mm" value="23.0" valueMax="25.0" valueMin="21.0">21–25 mm</quantity>
”). However, our limited data indicate a substantial overlap in size. Form “nigricans” (SI: Figure 
<quantity id="854F07EA3663226CFD3CF9F98766F9AD" box="[737,781,1571,1595]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="3.2" pageId="29" pageNumber="1571" unit="g" value="32.0">32g</quantity>
,h), first described from 
<collectingRegion id="807364ED3663226CFBFCF9F98004F9AD" box="[1057,1135,1571,1595]" country="Kenya" name="Taita/Taveta" pageId="29" pageNumber="1571">Taveta</collectingRegion>
by Aurivillius (1910c: 47), is dusky and this, together with the existence of a number of rare morphs (e.g. the bright orange form noted by 
<bibRefCitation id="2626D7FE3663226CFCD2F9B987F2F9ED" author="Larsen TB" box="[783,921,1635,1659]" pageId="29" pageNumber="1571" refId="ref25550" refString="Larsen TB. 1996. The butterflies of Kenya and their natural history. 2 nd edn. Oxford (UK): Oxford University Press." type="book" year="1996">Larsen 1996</bibRefCitation>
, p.143), indicates that the female of this species is polymorphic as well as variable, including at least two yellow morphs. 
<bibRefCitation id="2626D7FE3660226FFE9AFF72858CFF56" author="Talbot G" box="[327,487,168,192]" pageId="30" pageNumber="1572" pagination="102 - 112" refId="ref26272" refString="Talbot G. 1943 b. Notes on the genus Dixeia Talbot, with descriptions of new forms (Lep. Rhop. Pieridae). Proc R Entomol Soc Lond. 12: 102 - 112." type="journal article" year="1943">Talbot (1943b</bibRefCitation>
, p.106) gave a key to 11 named female forms for this species.
</paragraph>
